<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-747-062  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 747 062.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  August 14 1990 v4 n28 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple's presence felt at Siggraph. (Siggraph '90 conference)(Apple demonstrates new video compression technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Guglielmo, Connie.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Apple's Advanced Technology Group (ATG) demonstrated newproprietary video compression and decompression software at theSiggraph '90 conference in Dallas.andP;  The company showed digitizedcolor video and audio playing from a hard disk in multiple windowson Macintosh screens.andP;  Apple emphasizes that the new technology isin the research and development stage and not yet a sanctionedproduct, but notes that it views the software as a possibleextension to 32-bit QuickDraw and may eventually incorporate thetechnology into the Mac operating system.andP;  Other displays atSiggraph included Pixar's demonstration of new products that workwith its MacRenderMan photo-realistic rendering software.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     Conferences and MeetingsGraphics SystemsMultimedia TechnologyData CompressionVideo SystemsSpecial Interest Group on Computer GraphicsNew Technique.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Video compression may be part of OSandM;By Connie GuglielmoandM;Dallas -- Apple may have been relegated to a booth in the far corner, but theMac was all over the map at Siggraph '90 here last week.andM;The annual mecca for computer-graphics developers, Siggraph also gave Applean opportunity to showcase new graphics technologies being developed by itsAdvanced Technology Group, including video-compression software that may bepart of future operating systems.andM;In its booth, Apple demonstrated proprietary video-compression software thatwas shown playing digitized color video and audio from a hard disk inmultiple, movable, resizable windows on the Mac screen.andP;  Although it is stilljust a technology being worked on by ATG and not a sanctioned project, Applesaid the software is viewed as a possible extension to 32-bit QuickDraw thatmay be incor-porated into system software by late 1991.andM;&quot;Video compression is one of the Holy Grails of multimedia,&quot; said HughHempel, Apple marketing manager for technical markets.andP;  &quot;We see it as one ofthe strategic components of a multimedia computer and as an operating systemissue.&quot;andM;That Apple is serious about incorporating multimedia technologies -- sound,video and advanced graphics handling -- into the Macintosh system also isreflected in recent company ads seeking video, graphics, sound and imagingengineers (see Mac-WEEK, Aug.andP;  7).andM;Another ATG demonstration showcased radiosity, techniques for creatingphoto-realistic images.andP;  Radiosity takes into account the way objects absorband reflect light and the cumulative effect on a scene.andP;  Using a newtechnique called Incremental Radiosity, which allows the computer torecalculate only areas of change rather than recreating a new scene everytime an object is moved, Apple was able to modify full-color, 3-D scenesinteractively and quickly.andM;On the show floor at the three-day conference, Macintoshes dotted Pixar'shigh-profile booth, where the company demonstrated three new Macintoshproducts that work with its MacRenderMan photo-realistic rendering software,including its Showplace picture-composition software (see MacWEEK, Aug.andP;  7).andM;Apple also had three entries in the nightly Film and Video Theater.andO;Mac-based multimedia presentations, including a new educational presentationabout invertebrate animals (see related story, this page), dominated theshow's Hypermedia exhibit.andO;</TEXT></DOC>